Usage¶

Two main cell magics that have been implemented in manim_notebook are %%mango and %%manim.

%%mango cell magic¶

Using %%mango cell magic you can run manim code snippets inside that cell. Before using any of manim_notebook's cell magic you need to import manim_notebook first

In [1]:
from manim_notebook import *

import * takes care of all manim imports as well. Inorder to run manim code inside any cell just begin the first line of the cell with %%mango. Here's a simple example.

In [2]:
%%mango -l
circle = Circle(radius=3, stroke_width=5,
                stroke_color=YELLOW, fill_color=GREEN,
                fill_opacity=1)
self.play(ShowCreation(circle))
self.wait(4)
Out[2]:

Cool, isn't it? Notice that %%mango was supplied an additional argument -l. This was done inorder to render the video in low quality. %%mango supports all manim arguments. So you can use m for medium quality, --high-quality for high quality and no argument for production quality. If you want a list of all supported arguments use %%mango -h or %%mango --help. Another thing you might have noticed is that, output cell was moved to the right of input cell. This is the default behaviour but you can disable it by providing -x or --no-split as an argument to %%mango. The output video displayed on the browser has a frame size of 300x480(width, height) to better fit in the browser. You can change this frame size by using -z or --frame-size option. The resolution of the original video will still remain 480x854(resolution of low quality video). Remember -z option only changes the height and width of video being displayed on the browser and not the original video. Original video's resolution still depends on -l, -m or custom resolution passed via -r option.

By default you see progress bar and media in the output cell. You can use -v or --verbose option to see the complete output. Or you can use -q or --quiet option to hide progress bar as well. CAUTION: Quiet option also suppress errors.

But how does this code work without construct method and a class?
Behind the scenes all of the code written inside the cell is wrapped inside construct function and a class. The default class name chosen for this purpose is Foo and super class is Scene class. After stitching everything together the code is then written inside __temp__.py which then will be executed by manim. You can use --file option to change file name from __temp__.py to something else.
What if you want to create a graph? You cannot do so with Scene class. Fear not, you can configure super class using %%_config cell magic.
If you want to use other super class like GraphScene, you can do so by using %%_config -s GraphScene and override the default values. Additionally you can also change default class name using the -c option. So the overall cell magic looks like this.

In [3]:
%%_config -c PlotFunctions -s GraphScene
pass

-c option is used to set class name and -s option to set super class. If you can't remember everything, you can always use -h or --help option.

In [4]:
%%_config -h
pass

Instead of just using pass you can provide CONFIG dictionary and other class methods as cell body.

In [5]:
%%_config -c PlotFunctions -s GraphScene
CONFIG = {
    "x_min" : -10,
    "x_max" : 10.3,
    "y_min" : -1.5,
    "y_max" : 1.5,
    "graph_origin" : ORIGIN ,
    "function_color" : RED ,
    "axes_color" : GREEN,
    "x_labeled_nums" :range(-10,12,2),
} 
#these are class methods not ordinary functions, so you need to have 
#self as the first argument
def func_to_graph(self,x):
    return x**2

def func_to_graph2(self,x):
    return -x/10

Now that you have configured everything, you can write your main code.

In [6]:
%%mango -l
self.setup_axes(animate=True)
func_graph=self.get_graph(self.func_to_graph,
                          self.function_color)
func_graph2=self.get_graph(self.func_to_graph2)
vert_line = self.get_vertical_line_to_graph(TAU,
                            func_graph,color=YELLOW)

self.play(ShowCreation(func_graph),
          ShowCreation(func_graph2))
Out[6]:

If you want to graph functions like sin or cos you would probably import math or numpy. Simply importing them in a cell won't tell manim_notebook that you want to use those libraries. You will have to use %%header cell magic to do so.

In [7]:
%%header
import math

Now you can use math functions in your manim code.

Let's put everything together.

In [8]:
%%header
import math
In [9]:
%%_config -c ExampleApproximation -s GraphScene
CONFIG = {
    "function" : lambda x : np.cos(x), 
    "function_color" : BLUE,
    "taylor" : [lambda x: 1, lambda x: 1-x**2/2, lambda x: 1-x**2/math.factorial(2)+x**4/math.factorial(4),
                lambda x: 1-x**2/2+x**4/math.factorial(4)-x**6/math.factorial(6),
                lambda x: 1-x**2/math.factorial(2)+x**4/math.factorial(4)-x**6/math.factorial(6)+x**8/math.factorial(8),
                lambda x: 1-x**2/math.factorial(2)+x**4/math.factorial(4)-x**6/math.factorial(6)+x**8/math.factorial(8) - x**10/math.factorial(10)],
    "center_point" : 0,
    "approximation_color" : GREEN,
    "x_min" : -10,
    "x_max" : 10,
    "y_min" : -1,
    "y_max" : 1,
    "graph_origin" : ORIGIN ,
    "x_labeled_nums" :range(-10,12,2),

}
In [10]:
%%mango -l
self.setup_axes(animate=True)
func_graph = self.get_graph(
    self.function,
    self.function_color,
)
approx_graphs = [
    self.get_graph(
        f,
        self.approximation_color
    )
    for f in self.taylor
]

term_num = [
    TexMobject("n = " + str(n),aligned_edge=TOP)
    for n in range(0,8)]
#[t.to_edge(BOTTOM,buff=SMALL_BUFF) for t in term_num]


#term = TexMobject("")
#term.to_edge(BOTTOM,buff=SMALL_BUFF)
term = VectorizedPoint(3*DOWN)

approx_graph = VectorizedPoint(
    self.input_to_graph_point(self.center_point, func_graph)
)

self.play(
    ShowCreation(func_graph),
)
for n,graph in enumerate(approx_graphs):
    self.play(
        Transform(approx_graph, graph, run_time = 2),
        Transform(term,term_num[n])
    )
    self.wait()

That was all about %%mango. Now let's take a look at %%manim cell magic.

%%manim cell magic¶

If you like typing your code as a whole then you can use %%manim cell magic. It takes complete code as it's cell body.

Let's see how to use it.

In [11]:
%%manim -l
class Basics(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        circle = Circle(radius=3, stroke_width=5,
                        stroke_color=YELLOW,
                        fill_color=GREEN,
                        fill_opacity=1)
        self.play(ShowCreation(circle))
        self.wait(4)
Out[11]:

Simple, just like normal manim code. It also takes all those arguments which %%mango takes.

In [12]:
%%manim -lvx -z 450,800
class MoreShapes(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        circle = Circle(color=PURPLE_A)
        square = Square(fill_color=GOLD_B, fill_opacity=1, color=GOLD_A)
        square.move_to(UP+LEFT)
        circle.surround(square)
        rectangle = Rectangle(height=2, width=3)
        ellipse=Ellipse(width=3, height=1, color=RED)
        ellipse.shift(2*DOWN+2*RIGHT)
        pointer = CurvedArrow(2*RIGHT,5*RIGHT,color=MAROON_C)
        arrow = Arrow(LEFT,UP)
        arrow.next_to(circle,DOWN+LEFT)
        rectangle.next_to(arrow,DOWN+LEFT)
        ring=Annulus(inner_radius=.5, outer_radius=1, color=BLUE)
        ring.next_to(ellipse, RIGHT)

        self.add(pointer)
        self.play(FadeIn(square))
        self.play(Rotating(square),FadeIn(circle))
        self.play(GrowArrow(arrow))
        self.play(GrowFromCenter(rectangle), GrowFromCenter(ellipse), GrowFromCenter(ring))

                                                                           
Media will be written to ./media/. You can change this behavior with the --media_dir flag.

                                                                                           

File ready at /home/akash/akash/media/videos/__temp__/480p15/MoreShapes.mp4

Played 4 animations
Out[12]:

In the above example the arguments passed to manim were -l for low quality, -v for verbose, -x to prevent split and -r to set custom frame size(not be confused with actual video's resolution which is still 480x854). If you have more than one class, you can display multiple videos either by providing required classes as argument,

In [13]:
%%manim Class1 Class2 Class3 -l
class Class1(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        square = Square()
        self.play(ShowCreation(square))
        self.wait(4)
class Class2(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        circle = Circle()
        self.play(ShowCreation(circle))
        self.wait(4)
class Class3(Scene):
    def construct(self):
        triangle = Triangle()
        self.play(ShowCreation(triangle))
        self.wait(4)
